WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.800
Hi, I'm Jacqueline Nolis. I'm a data scientist. I'm joined here today by Heather Nolis, machine

00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:20.100
learning engineer from T-Mobile, and this talk is about how we did something we're so

00:00:20.100 --> 00:00:25.799
excited about, and it's how we got R working in R in production environments.

00:00:25.799 --> 00:00:28.719
So what does it mean to put something into production? And we heard about that a little

00:00:28.719 --> 00:00:34.119
bit already during the keynotes. But we think about it like this. With data science, there's

00:00:34.119 --> 00:00:38.520
like two types of data science. There's A-type analysis, where you're trying to figure out

00:00:38.520 --> 00:00:44.919
an idea, do an exploration, figure out something, and your deliverable is an idea.

00:00:44.919 --> 00:00:48.720
And then there's the building type, where you make a machine learning model, and you

00:00:48.720 --> 00:00:52.880
want to run it. You want to run it over and over, like if you're designing a product recommendation

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:55.000
engine for a website.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:00.119
And so at T-Mobile, we really define putting code into production as making it so that

00:01:00.119 --> 00:01:04.680
customers can interact with it. And this morning, we heard about making dashboards that many

00:01:04.680 --> 00:01:09.519
users can use at once, maybe 20. Well, we have 70 million customers. And we just merged

00:01:09.519 --> 00:01:14.120
with Sprint, who has another 60 million customers. So we have lots and lots of people.

00:01:14.120 --> 00:01:17.120
And when we're talking about machine learning, we're really talking about making machine

00:01:17.120 --> 00:01:21.599
learning models that all of those people can use. Hopefully not all at once, but all of

00:01:21.599 --> 00:01:24.559
them could use.

00:01:24.559 --> 00:01:29.320
And so the project was called AI at T-Mobile. So T-Mobile has been doing data science for

00:01:29.320 --> 00:01:33.959
many years. And we have lots of people who are very good at things like that exploration,

00:01:33.959 --> 00:01:37.800
building churn models on our customers, that sort of reporting work.

00:01:37.800 --> 00:01:42.519
But we didn't have very much of putting machine learning models that we developed into production

00:01:42.519 --> 00:01:46.959
environments so our customers can use them. So this project was to actually take machine

00:01:46.959 --> 00:01:50.480
learning and get it in front of our customers in a way that really improves the customer

00:01:50.480 --> 00:01:56.480
experience. And I say that because T-Mobile has a really big deal about being the uncarrier.

00:01:56.480 --> 00:02:00.040
So we're not going to make you have to go deal with chat bots and have bad experiences.

00:02:00.040 --> 00:02:02.919
We want things to be pleasant for our customers.

00:02:02.919 --> 00:02:08.419
So our first scope was customer care messaging. So right now, today, you can go on your phone

00:02:08.419 --> 00:02:12.199
and you can text T-Mobile. And you can say something like, I don't have my coverage is

00:02:12.199 --> 00:02:17.119
bad. And a human being at a desk will respond back to you and help you try to diagnose your

00:02:17.160 --> 00:02:22.000
problem. And so we can do that through text message. We can do that through Facebook Messenger.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:26.559
You can slide into T-Mobile's DMs and send a message and a human being will respond back

00:02:26.559 --> 00:02:30.639
to you or use our in-app messaging. So we have all of this text data. We have all of

00:02:30.639 --> 00:02:34.639
this stuff that's ripe for natural language processing. And our objective was let's get

00:02:34.639 --> 00:02:38.800
some machine learning around that that makes things better for the customer.

00:02:38.800 --> 00:02:44.199
So our first particular use case was consider, you know, our customers, they talk in all

00:02:44.199 --> 00:02:48.240
sorts of weird ways. So suppose we had one particular customer come to us and say, this

00:02:48.240 --> 00:02:54.520
high bill shall not pass, which is an utterance we had never seen before. And, you know, we

00:02:54.520 --> 00:02:58.399
have the goal, if we have an agent at a computer who's responding to these messages and maybe

00:02:58.399 --> 00:03:02.479
has like eight conversations going on at once, we have the goal to try and prep them. That

00:03:02.479 --> 00:03:06.440
like, oh, it would be really helpful if that agent when they started the conversation already

00:03:06.440 --> 00:03:10.800
knew the status of the customer's bill. And so what is our method? Well, we're going to

00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:14.880
build a classification engine with machine learning. So in this case, this high bill

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:20.160
shall not pass would be classified as a bill breakdown message. And further, we can improve

00:03:20.160 --> 00:03:24.440
that by actually using customer data. So if we know something about this customer, like

00:03:24.440 --> 00:03:28.479
if we know their recent account activity, their current signal strength, their bill

00:03:28.479 --> 00:03:32.600
status, like maybe it's overdue, that may change what we want to show the agent. So

00:03:32.600 --> 00:03:36.919
you can imagine if a customer just got their account suspended, like 20 minutes ago, and

00:03:36.919 --> 00:03:41.639
they come to T-Mobile and they say, hi, well, we probably know what they're talking about.

00:03:41.639 --> 00:03:45.720
So we can use that data to help inform our machine learning prediction. So how do we

00:03:45.720 --> 00:03:51.520
create the models in R? Well, our workflow was like this. One, we would start by using

00:03:51.520 --> 00:03:55.839
R markdown for exploratory analysis. So we would take those many conversations that we

00:03:55.839 --> 00:04:00.520
have between customers and agents, and we would try and build an understanding of what

00:04:00.520 --> 00:04:03.880
happens on them. What are the things people kind of talk about? And then once we get a

00:04:03.880 --> 00:04:07.759
better idea, we would build a machine learning model in R, and then we'd save those models

00:04:07.759 --> 00:04:12.720
to flat files. And in particular, we would do the model building with R markdown so that

00:04:12.720 --> 00:04:16.119
we could actually have a log of exactly how it was built, what data went in, how well

00:04:16.119 --> 00:04:21.119
the fit went, and then we'd save all of that. And then before we even get to actually like

00:04:21.119 --> 00:04:24.959
deploying or anything, we need to get the business people to be excited about this.

00:04:24.959 --> 00:04:31.799
So we show our model off with a shiny demo. So after we do the exploratory analysis, we

00:04:31.799 --> 00:04:36.320
would start building a model. We ended up building neural networks using Keras. So Keras

00:04:36.320 --> 00:04:41.239
is a really, really cool R package from R studio that lets you very easily build deep

00:04:41.239 --> 00:04:45.399
learning models. And so for us, we ended up using a convolutional neural network, which

00:04:45.399 --> 00:04:49.920
is a particular type of neural network, to do the text parsing and understand what was

00:04:49.920 --> 00:04:54.079
the topic going on in the text. But we also had to bring in all those other data types

00:04:54.079 --> 00:04:58.920
too, like what's the order status or, you know, is their account currently suspended.

00:04:58.920 --> 00:05:03.200
And so we had more traditional neural networks parse that data. And then we put that all

00:05:03.200 --> 00:05:08.440
together with one final neural network that outputs which classification. So in this case,

00:05:08.440 --> 00:05:13.359
we would train a neural network that would learn that unlock my phone with a recent order,

00:05:13.359 --> 00:05:17.920
that has an 80% chance of being categorized and unlocked.

00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:21.200
So we built these networks, and we were pretty excited about them. But we have these problems

00:05:21.200 --> 00:05:24.640
because we'd go into meetings with the business people and be like, guys, we're having look

00:05:24.640 --> 00:05:31.119
at these ROC curves. 80.8. And we're like, whatever. And so we had one meeting with some

00:05:31.119 --> 00:05:35.220
business people, and 10 minutes before, we're like, let's just throw it in a Shiny demo.

00:05:35.220 --> 00:05:39.119
And this changed the game. The fact that we actually had Shiny demos where a business

00:05:39.119 --> 00:05:43.160
person could type in, I want to unlock my phone, and actually watch that would be classified

00:05:43.160 --> 00:05:49.600
as unlock. This got us, and I'm not exaggerating, millions of dollars of funding, multiple people

00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:53.079
added to our team. And it's because we could take this, show it to a business person who

00:05:53.079 --> 00:05:56.279
showed it to the director, who showed it to the VP, who eventually we ended up showing

00:05:56.279 --> 00:06:01.880
this stuff to the CIO, all because we had a really nice Shiny demo that we built around

00:06:01.880 --> 00:06:04.720
our models. And so if you look, this doesn't look quite

00:06:04.720 --> 00:06:09.040
like a normal, whew, it really didn't look normal. That doesn't look like quite a normal

00:06:09.040 --> 00:06:14.839
Shiny demo, and it's because we decided to spend an extra day using, I'm going to give

00:06:14.839 --> 00:06:20.160
this a little wiggle. Let's see if that's okay. We spent an extra day making the HTML

00:06:20.160 --> 00:06:27.320
look nicer, and that really, again, gave us a really polished professional view.

00:06:27.320 --> 00:06:31.440
So I'm a data scientist, and I'm very comfortable doing all the things I just showed, but putting

00:06:31.440 --> 00:06:34.760
things in production, deployments, when I started this project, a lot of that stuff

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:39.839
was new for me. But thankfully, our team had machine learning engineers to help.

00:06:39.839 --> 00:06:46.079
Okay. Am I on? Hello? Can anybody hear me? There we go. Okay. So when it came time to

00:06:46.079 --> 00:06:51.839
put our models in production, I was handed these R files, and I was a Java developer,

00:06:51.839 --> 00:06:55.600
and I was like, I really don't know what to do with this or how to get it in a place that

00:06:55.600 --> 00:07:01.579
can interface with our 70-plus million customers. And so every single person had told our team,

00:07:01.579 --> 00:07:06.480
if you want to do machine learning in production, you have to use Python. But I just handled

00:07:06.480 --> 00:07:11.600
a really cool R project, so I was like, hiring data scientists to redo all this work in Python

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:17.040
and redo an analysis seems silly. Since the model's already built and it's very good and

00:07:17.040 --> 00:07:21.480
the business people really like it, I could convert it to Python and then put it in production,

00:07:21.480 --> 00:07:26.559
but that seems silly. So I was like, what if we just do it all in R, and what if we

00:07:26.559 --> 00:07:30.959
take out this double work that people assume that you have where you have to rewrite things

00:07:30.959 --> 00:07:36.959
for 70 million people using Python? So, yeah, the radical idea here was what if we treat

00:07:36.959 --> 00:07:42.559
R like a real programming language? Because it is a programming language. And so how things

00:07:42.559 --> 00:07:47.079
work on our team is we have all of our stuff in repositories, as soon as you make a commit,

00:07:47.079 --> 00:07:50.880
and so this is the way any of our Java or Node projects would work, as soon as you make

00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:56.440
a commit to a repository, some software called Jenkins builds it up into its final project,

00:07:56.440 --> 00:08:01.559
Marathon, it's kind of like off-brand Kubernetes, orchestrates the container development and

00:08:01.559 --> 00:08:05.239
mazes hosts and replicates those containers for you, so we have a really nice system in

00:08:05.239 --> 00:08:08.600
place for Java projects where you can just make a commit and then instantly something's

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:12.880
in production and it's facing with your customers, so I was like, well, let's make R do that

00:08:12.880 --> 00:08:19.320
and avoid this whole Python trip entirely. And so the first thing that we had to do is

00:08:19.320 --> 00:08:26.160
we had to convert our R models into an API, and so what an API is, is right now if I was

00:08:26.160 --> 00:08:31.000
to go on my phone and type weather.com, it returns back some website for me, and that's

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:35.840
an API, it's just a way of using the Internet to send a message, I want to go to weather.com

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:39.880
and get some information back, here's the entire website, that's weather.com. You can

00:08:39.880 --> 00:08:44.880
also use it with model input and output, so we want you to predict how long this stem

00:08:44.880 --> 00:08:50.320
length is, send it to the model via an API and then it comes back, okay, I have a prediction

00:08:50.320 --> 00:08:54.440
for you, so it's very, very easy. So once you have a REST controller, which defines

00:08:54.440 --> 00:08:58.979
all the little slashes that you would put on your website URL, you just start plumber

00:08:58.979 --> 00:09:03.780
on your R model and now you can go into your browser and type in something and immediately

00:09:03.780 --> 00:09:07.539
get information from our model back despite not being close to it, which is really cool

00:09:07.539 --> 00:09:11.179
and that's how all of our services talk to each other in engineering is via API calls,

00:09:11.179 --> 00:09:15.460
so this way we can have Java talking to Python, talking to R, it all makes sense because it

00:09:15.460 --> 00:09:20.380
all uses the Internet. And then the way that we package everything

00:09:20.380 --> 00:09:25.419
up on our team is with containers, and so what containers are is if I was to go to Best

00:09:25.419 --> 00:09:30.340
Buy right now and buy a laptop and I really wanted to put Jaclyn's model on it, I would

00:09:30.340 --> 00:09:34.979
have to go home, I would sit down, I would install, I don't know, my Internet and I would

00:09:34.979 --> 00:09:39.099
install Outlook and then I would install R studio and then all of the packages needed

00:09:39.099 --> 00:09:43.419
for R studio and it gets quite cumbersome to set up the machine and then of course I'm

00:09:43.419 --> 00:09:46.820
using a more recent version of the package than she was using, so her model still won't

00:09:46.820 --> 00:09:51.820
run even though she emailed me and I downloaded it, and so what Docker is essentially is just

00:09:51.820 --> 00:09:56.460
a way to write down all of those instructions so that way they're repeatable forever, so

00:09:56.460 --> 00:10:00.940
that way any time a new virtual machine is spun up, a little container on it can just

00:10:00.940 --> 00:10:04.700
repeat those Docker images and they have the exact same thing that I was looking at when

00:10:04.700 --> 00:10:08.700
I was on my laptop or the same thing Jaclyn was looking at when she was on her laptop,

00:10:08.700 --> 00:10:12.940
so I can then take my code to someone who doesn't have R installed on their computer

00:10:12.940 --> 00:10:18.739
and if they have Docker it will run on their machine.

00:10:18.739 --> 00:10:23.619
And so the first problem that we actually had is I have this container, we used a rocker

00:10:23.619 --> 00:10:28.020
based image, rocker is a company that makes these R, I guess it's an organization that

00:10:28.020 --> 00:10:31.820
makes these R based Docker images, so you can just kind of copy the work that they've

00:10:31.820 --> 00:10:36.020
done and start from there, and the first thing is so I have R in a Docker image and I have

00:10:36.020 --> 00:10:41.020
Jaclyn's model, but the big problem is that R Keras actually requires Python, so you have

00:10:41.020 --> 00:10:45.140
to call Python on the end, so we're like, okay, we have this Docker image that contains

00:10:45.140 --> 00:10:50.580
R, it contains our studio, it contains our model, so, okay, let's put in the actual Python

00:10:50.580 --> 00:10:54.780
that's required to make this run, so, okay, we finally get Python installed, everything

00:10:54.780 --> 00:11:00.679
should be good, but it's not, because Plumber doesn't support HTTPS and we're a big enterprise

00:11:00.679 --> 00:11:05.979
and so we have to have really secure connections between stuff, so HTTP was not sufficient,

00:11:05.979 --> 00:11:10.179
so inside of our Docker container, okay, we'll add an Apache 2 server that sits in the same

00:11:10.179 --> 00:11:15.900
container as our R code and all it does is take HTTPS request, converts them to HTTP,

00:11:15.900 --> 00:11:21.219
does the model processing and then passes it back through, so now we have R and we have

00:11:21.219 --> 00:11:25.940
the model and we have Python and we have this Apache 2 server and so it's getting quite

00:11:25.940 --> 00:11:30.619
hefty, and that was actually the next trouble that we ran into, we deployed it, it went

00:11:30.619 --> 00:11:36.059
through our Python, it went out perfect, but it was nearly 5 gigs in size by the time that

00:11:36.059 --> 00:11:40.539
you get all the dependencies and everything that you need and so this is a quick breakdown

00:11:40.539 --> 00:11:44.619
of what our container actually looked like, so if you look, the bulk of the container

00:11:44.619 --> 00:11:51.419
ends up being Python and our DevOps team was like you guys can't keep running 5 gig containers,

00:11:51.419 --> 00:11:56.700
you've taken down entire T mobile clusters, like huge problems are occurring because you're

00:11:56.700 --> 00:12:02.140
throwing this out there, so we said, okay, we'll do some work and so we switched the

00:12:02.140 --> 00:12:09.780
full version of Anaconda Python, we removed R studio from the Docker image and we spent

00:12:09.780 --> 00:12:14.219
a lot of time removing all these unnecessary Linux and R and Python libraries to get the

00:12:14.219 --> 00:12:18.460
container size small enough that DevOps would say, okay, we're totally fine with you using

00:12:18.460 --> 00:12:22.059
R now because you've made it small enough, it contains all of our security requirements,

00:12:22.059 --> 00:12:26.979
it contains everything it needs to run, it looks good to go.

00:12:26.979 --> 00:12:32.020
And we did it, so we deployed a model in R, the first T mobile's first customer facing

00:12:32.020 --> 00:12:36.619
deep learning model and it was all completely written in R, so it's an R native API, it

00:12:36.619 --> 00:12:40.979
has TensorFlow, it's super, super small and it's just as secure as everybody wants it

00:12:40.979 --> 00:12:46.979
to be and is required, so really cool.

00:12:46.979 --> 00:12:51.299
But we learned a lot of stuff in doing this, and so I think that the first thing that we

00:12:51.299 --> 00:12:54.700
learned is, you know, people came to us in the beginning and said you have to write this

00:12:54.700 --> 00:13:00.140
in Python, we won't support you doing it in R, but we tested our APIs at 50 times T

00:13:00.140 --> 00:13:05.419
mobile's maximum load and R performed just fine, so for us, using R and Plumber was at

00:13:05.419 --> 00:13:09.859
very close parity performance wise with Python and Flask, and then R was really good for

00:13:09.859 --> 00:13:14.539
us to do the quick data exploration that got us the idea to build this model in the first

00:13:14.539 --> 00:13:19.340
place, and then the shiny demos are what really, really sold our project, and there's not really

00:13:19.340 --> 00:13:23.619
an equivalent for Python, you can't just quickly throw a few lines of code and take it to a

00:13:23.619 --> 00:13:28.900
business person and have it passed around like that, and most importantly, language

00:13:28.900 --> 00:13:31.820
is never the fail point for our project.

00:13:31.820 --> 00:13:36.419
It was always security concerns of the container being too big or Python being giant or some

00:13:36.419 --> 00:13:40.260
dependency projects, but it was never R that was the reason that we were struggling at

00:13:40.260 --> 00:13:43.460
any point.

00:13:43.460 --> 00:13:46.780
And the next thing we learned is that it's really, really critical to work in a flat

00:13:46.780 --> 00:13:50.500
team, so traditionally how this works is data scientists, they build the model and they'll

00:13:50.500 --> 00:13:54.940
send it over to the engineers, the engineers rewrite in Python, and then they'll deliver

00:13:54.940 --> 00:13:57.820
it to the business, but the business wants it a little bit different, so it goes back

00:13:57.820 --> 00:14:02.179
to the data scientists, and we stopped that chain of telephone, and we're like what if

00:14:02.179 --> 00:14:05.859
we all just sit together, so our team was literally two machine learning engineers,

00:14:05.859 --> 00:14:10.500
three data scientists, a Java engineer, and then our business person all together at the

00:14:10.500 --> 00:14:16.140
same table every single day, so that way if the machine learning engineers can be developing

00:14:16.140 --> 00:14:19.140
the API and then the data scientists find something new they want to do and you can

00:14:19.140 --> 00:14:22.260
just talk to each other instead of waiting two months until you get a finished product

00:14:22.260 --> 00:14:29.419
and then trying to iterate on that, so it made it a very, very, very agile structure.

00:14:29.419 --> 00:14:35.179
So with all that work, it was a lot of work, you're very excited about it, fun work, where

00:14:35.179 --> 00:14:36.179
are we today?

00:14:36.179 --> 00:14:37.179
Well, first off.

00:14:37.179 --> 00:14:38.179
Your mic's not on.

00:14:38.179 --> 00:14:39.179
Oh.

00:14:39.179 --> 00:14:40.179
Yeah, okay, cool, great.

00:14:40.179 --> 00:14:47.419
The first thing is we have R in production right now in a way that any iPhone user in

00:14:47.419 --> 00:14:54.059
the audience right now, you guys can hit R code, make R code run, which is I don't know,

00:14:54.059 --> 00:14:57.979
I never thought there would be that day, never mind, I was part of that day.

00:14:57.979 --> 00:15:00.419
So in particular, there's a product called Apple Business Chat.

00:15:00.419 --> 00:15:04.900
So about a year ago, Apple released this way for companies to actually use iMessage.

00:15:04.900 --> 00:15:09.380
So if you search for T-Mobile on your iPhone, you can start a chat with T-Mobile, and it's

00:15:09.380 --> 00:15:15.140
like a nicely colored branded box, but T-Mobile doesn't get to know your telephone number.

00:15:15.140 --> 00:15:17.219
All they know is that you're an anonymous person.

00:15:17.219 --> 00:15:20.979
And so the first thing T-Mobile used to do was ask you, hey, are you a customer or not?

00:15:20.979 --> 00:15:24.460
Because they needed to know if they wanted to route you to customer carriers or sales.

00:15:24.460 --> 00:15:27.340
And so we'd ask the customer and get a yes or no back.

00:15:27.340 --> 00:15:29.179
And to us, this was ridiculous, right?

00:15:29.179 --> 00:15:31.219
If someone says, why is my bill so high?

00:15:31.219 --> 00:15:32.219
Of course they should go to customer.

00:15:32.219 --> 00:15:36.780
If someone says, I want to switch to T-Mobile, they should not go to customer.

00:15:36.780 --> 00:15:39.219
And so we built a machine learning model around that.

00:15:39.219 --> 00:15:43.140
And so now every time someone in iMessage starts a new conversation, it sends it to

00:15:43.140 --> 00:15:44.539
the R machine learning model.

00:15:44.539 --> 00:15:48.059
If the R machine learning model is confident they're a customer or confident they're not,

00:15:48.059 --> 00:15:49.700
then they don't see this picker at all.

00:15:49.700 --> 00:15:53.140
If we kind of get unsure, if they just say hi, then they would still get the picker like

00:15:53.140 --> 00:15:54.140
old.

00:15:54.140 --> 00:15:58.219
So we've actually used machine learning and AI to make the customer experience more streamlined

00:15:58.219 --> 00:16:02.820
rather than to do an annoying chatbot kind of like, please say unlock, you know?

