00:18:55.760 --> 00:19:01.160
Because this specific instance is a Keras model that isn't necessarily specific to R

00:19:01.160 --> 00:19:04.479
or Python, do you need R or Python at all?

00:19:04.479 --> 00:19:08.699
Is it because of like the API wrapper or text preprocessing?

00:19:08.699 --> 00:19:14.599
So I think that from my perspective, it was that I was handed a model in R. Why would

00:19:14.599 --> 00:19:15.839
I rebuild that?

00:19:15.839 --> 00:19:16.839
Right?

00:19:16.839 --> 00:19:18.040
Like it already exists.

00:19:18.040 --> 00:19:22.000
And so the exploration was done in R. And so that's why we decided to support our native

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:23.000
model.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:24.000
Yeah.

00:19:24.119 --> 00:19:26.760
So what we do, you know, with us, we first take the conversation and then we remove the

00:19:26.760 --> 00:19:27.760
weird characters.

00:19:27.760 --> 00:19:28.760
And then we do this.

00:19:28.760 --> 00:19:29.760
And then we feed it to the model.

00:19:29.760 --> 00:19:31.880
And, you know, some of our engineers are like, wow, we could technically run TensorFlow in

00:19:31.880 --> 00:19:32.880
Java.

00:19:32.880 --> 00:19:35.719
But then we'd have to figure out what to do with all those steps.

00:19:35.719 --> 00:19:37.319
And it's like, well, we'd have to keep them in R anyway.

00:19:37.319 --> 00:19:38.319
So eh.

00:19:38.319 --> 00:19:39.319
And so, yeah.

00:19:39.319 --> 00:19:42.319
So I think that normally the argument that people put forth is like, oh, well, it's more

00:19:42.319 --> 00:19:43.760
scalable and we support Java.

00:19:43.760 --> 00:19:48.160
And it's like we just used all the Java tools that exist and did it in R and it worked just

00:19:48.160 --> 00:19:49.160
fine.

00:19:49.160 --> 00:19:50.839
And then you eliminate the double work.

00:19:51.839 --> 00:19:52.839
Okay.

00:19:52.839 --> 00:19:55.920
I have a question for your neural network.

00:19:55.920 --> 00:20:01.040
So based on the application, it looks to me it's like a natural language processing.

00:20:01.040 --> 00:20:02.319
So it should be the sequence model.

00:20:02.319 --> 00:20:05.199
But you mentioned about the convolutionary neural network.

00:20:05.199 --> 00:20:07.000
Can you give me some explanation here?

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:08.000
Yeah.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:10.760
So we tried actually started with a recurrent neural network.

00:20:10.760 --> 00:20:14.959
And we found that the recurrent neural network did not perform as well as a convolutional

00:20:14.959 --> 00:20:15.959
neural network.

00:20:15.959 --> 00:20:20.239
Our suspicion is because of the classification, usually someone says, Bill, so high.

00:20:20.239 --> 00:20:23.160
And those three words, it doesn't matter what's all around it.

00:20:23.160 --> 00:20:27.000
So that's our suspicion for why a convolutional neural network works slightly better.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:31.479
But we were actually surprised at how shallow the optimal networks ended up being.

00:20:31.479 --> 00:20:36.119
We were expecting to have five layers and recurrents, but it's really one convolutional

00:20:36.119 --> 00:20:43.239
layer, one or two dense layers, and then that's the whole network.

00:20:43.239 --> 00:20:47.020
You spoke about making your app secure.

00:20:47.020 --> 00:20:48.359
Can you speak a bit about that?

00:20:48.680 --> 00:20:52.319
Two-factor authentication and how you're able to achieve that using R?

00:20:52.319 --> 00:20:53.319
Yeah.

00:20:53.319 --> 00:20:56.359
So all of our stuff right now is accessed from within our network.

00:20:56.359 --> 00:20:58.199
So we don't have to do an Apigee authentication.

00:20:58.199 --> 00:21:00.800
But if we did an Apigee authentication, it would be very simple.

00:21:00.800 --> 00:21:03.280
We would just make the relative API calls.

00:21:03.280 --> 00:21:06.920
One thing that we did do is that all of our messages have to be passed encrypted.

00:21:06.920 --> 00:21:11.160
And so we used a, there's a library that's Sodium that's really good in encryption.

00:21:11.160 --> 00:21:12.599
And then you can decrypt in Java.

00:21:12.599 --> 00:21:17.680
So we were being passed things from Java that we then had to decrypt and then re-encrypt

00:21:17.680 --> 00:21:23.800
in R. And so we use that all using the Sodium library to do that, which is AES-256 encryption.

00:21:23.800 --> 00:21:24.839
So it's pretty secure.

